org.gridgain.grid.lang.utils
Class GridConcurrentLinkedQueue<E>

java.lang.Object
  java.util.AbstractCollection<E>
      org.gridgain.grid.lang.utils.GridSerializableCollection<E>
          org.gridgain.grid.lang.utils.GridConcurrentLinkedQueue<E>
All Implemented Interfaces:
Serializable, Iterable<E>, Collection<E>, Queue<E>
public class GridConcurrentLinkedQueue<E>
extends GridSerializableCollection<E>
implements Queue<E>

Concurrent queue which fixes infinite growth of JDK ConcurrentLinkedQueue implementation. On top of that, it provides public access to internal 'nodes', so middle elements of the queue can be accessed immediately.

The problem of JDK implementation is that it must follow regular queue semantics and will only work if you call Queue.offer(Object) and Queue.poll(), and will leave nullified nodes mingling around if Collection.remove(Object) was called which can lead to memory leaks.
